1 Summary
This report presents the solution I propose at Blood Glucose Level Prediction
(BGLP) Challenge. This document is part of the ﬁnal submission for the course
Mathematical Foundations of Advanced Machine Learning held by Professor
Leow at University of Illinois, Chicago.
Accurately predicting blood glucose levels can signiﬁcantly enhance the health
and quality of life for individuals with diabetes. By anticipating when blood
glucose is nearing dangerous levels, patients can take preventive actions to avoid
hypoglycemia or hyperglycemia and the associated health risks. The quest for
an advanced artiﬁcial pancreas has fueled growing interest in leveraging machine
learning (ML) techniques to enhance the precision of these predictions.
Research demonstrates that predicting blood glucose levels is feasible using a
combination of physiological signals and lifestyle data, including information on
meals, stress, and exercise. Physiological signals like heart rate and galvanic skin
response can be measured directly using sensors, providing objective, continuous
data. In contrast, other factors such as meal timing, carbohydrate estimates, and
stress levels are often self-reported, which introduces variability and potential
inaccuracies.
Modern continuous glucose monitoring systems provide excellent sources of data
to train machine learning models to predict future glucose levels, and the aim
of this project is to present multiple approaches for predicting blood glucose
levels for diabetics up to 1 h into the future. All the methods have been trained
and tested on the Ohio T1DM dataset for blood glucose level prediction. The
evaluation is quantitatively performed through the standard root-mean-squared
error (RMSE) and through the Clark Error Grid.
2 Dataset
The OhioT1DM Dataset [3], used in this project, was developed to promote re-
search in blood glucose level prediction. It contains eight weeks of data from 12
2 C. Amodeo
individuals with type 1 diabetes, collected through continuous glucose monitor-
ing (CGM), insulin delivery records, physiological sensors, and self-reported life-
event data. Participants were on insulin pump therapy and used either Medtronic
530G or 630G models with Enlite CGM sensors. Physiological data such as heart
rate, galvanic skin response (GSR), and skin temperature were collected using
ﬁtness bands (Basis Peak or Empatica Embrace). Additionally, the dataset in-
cludes self-reported data on meals, exercise, sleep, stress, and illness, making
it suitable for exploring the interaction between various factors aﬀecting blood
glucose levels. For a detailed description of the diﬀerent measurements included
in the dataset, refer to Table 1. A visualization of various physiological and event
data from a sample period is provided in Figure 1.

3 Methods
This section presents the methodology employed in this project and is orga-
nized into several key parts. The ﬁrst part, Dataset Exploration, involves an
in-depth analysis of the OhioT1DM dataset, followed by the preparation steps
necessary to transform the raw data into a suitable format for modeling. The
second part, Problem Statement, clearly deﬁnes the objectives of the predic-
tion task. The third and fourth parts focus on two diﬀerent models: Baseline
Model, which uses linear regression on features extracted using the automated
framework from tsfresh, and Long Short Term Memory Network, which
describes a more complex deep learning approach utilizing a Long Short-Term
Memory (LSTM) network to predict blood glucose levels.
3.1 Data Exploration
The OhioT1DM dataset contains signiﬁcant amounts of missing data, which
must be addressed to ensure the accuracy of predictive models. Speciﬁcally,

example, the finger column is missing 97.53% of its values, and the carbInput
and bolus columns are also highly sparse, with missing rates of 98.84% and

Based on methodologies suggested by the literature [4], missing cbg values
are restored using cubic splines. For other covariates, columns with low data
density, such as finger, are left as-is, as interpolation is not appropriate due
to the sparsity. The columns Basal, GSR, and HR are interpolated using cubic
splines to approximate the missing values more accurately.
Furthermore, an examination of the covariates reveals how they relate to the
target variable (cbg). Speciﬁcally, the correlation between the finger values
and the cbg should ideally be close to 1, indicating a strong relationship. How-
ever, the observed deviations suggest that patients might be incorrectly inputting
their ﬁnger glucose values, possibly due to being uninformed or errors in self-
reporting. This discrepancy points to the challenges associated with relying on

3.2 Problem Statement
The ability to accurately predict blood glucose levels within a speciﬁc time win-
dow is crucial for the eﬀective management of diabetes, particularly for closed-
loop insulin delivery systems [5]. Figure 4 provides a visualization of continu-
ous glucose monitoring (CGM) measurements over time, highlighting diﬀerent
glucose ranges: hypoglycemia (HYPO), normoglycemia (NORMO), and hyper-
glycemia (HYPER). Eﬀective prediction of glucose levels enables state-of-the-art
closed-loop systems, such as the Medtronic MiniMed 780G, to optimize insulin
delivery, thereby minimizing glucose variability. This is especially important af-
ter meals or physical activities, where glucose levels can ﬂuctuate rapidly. In
these scenarios, the system’s ability to anticipate glucose trends and make in-
formed decisions on insulin dosage plays a critical role in maintaining glucose
levels within the target range, reducing the risk of both hyperglycemia and hy-
poglycemia. Consequently, improving the accuracy of glucose forecasting is a key
component in advancing the performance of automated insulin delivery systems
and ensuring better outcomes for individuals with diabetes.

3.3 Proposed Framework
Figure 5 illustrates the proposed framework for blood glucose prediction. The
OhioT1DM dataset, containing CGM data and other physiological signals de-
scribed in Table 1, is ﬁrst preprocessed to ensure consistency and alignment
across all features. The preprocessing block combines continuous glucose mon-
itoring (CGM) measurements with additional signals, such as heart rate, skin
temperature, and insulin dosage, to create a complete dataset for model training.
The framework includes two models for glucose prediction: a baseline linear
regression model and a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) model [2]. The lin-
ear regression model is used as a benchmark to evaluate the added beneﬁts of
employing a more complex deep learning model like LSTM. The LSTM network
leverages its capability to capture temporal dependencies in sequential data to
provide improved glucose prediction.
Model performance is evaluated using both standard machine learning met-
rics and clinical metrics. Speciﬁcally, the models are assessed using the Mean
Squared Error (MSE), Mean Absolute Error (MAE), and their respective roots,
providing a quantitative measure of prediction accuracy. In addition, clinical rele-
vance is analyzed through the Clarke Error Grid [1], which categorizes prediction
accuracy in terms of clinical safety. Both models are tested over 30-minute and
60-minute prediction windows to evaluate their ability to forecast future glucose
levels over diﬀerent time horizons eﬀectively.

3.4 Baseline Model
In the baseline model, feature engineering was performed using the tsfresh
library to extract relevant features from the time-series data. Each physiolog-
ical signal, including heart rate, and galvanic skin response, was divided into
5-minute non-overlapping windows. For each window, several statistical and fre-
quency domain features were extracted to capture the dynamics of the signals
eﬀectively.
These features are summarized in Table 2.
Feature Description
Mean Average value of the signal in a 5-minute window.
Standard Deviation Measures the spread or variability of the signal.
Skewness Indicates the asymmetry of the signal distribution.
Kurtosis Describes the shape of the distribution, focusing on
the tails.
Autocorrelation Correlation of the signal with a lagged version of
itself, to identify repeating patterns.
Peak Frequency The most prominent frequency component in the
signal, revealing periodic behavior.
Energy Sum of the squared values of the signal, reﬂecting
signal intensity.
Table 2: Features extracted using the tsfresh library for the baseline model.
These engineered features were then used as inputs in a classical linear re-
gression framework for blood glucose forecasting. The linear regression model
aims to ﬁnd a linear relationship between the set of features X and the target
variable y, which represents future CGM values. The mathematical formulation
for linear regression is:
ˆy = X · w + b,
where X represents the matrix of features, w represents the vector of weights
for each feature, and b is the bias term. The model parameters (w, b) are opti-
mized by minimizing the MSE, to achieve the best ﬁt for the linear relationship
between the features and the predicted glucose levels.
To prevent overﬁtting and address the issue of multicollinearity, ridge regres-
sion, a form of regularized linear regression, was employed. Ridge regression
adds an L
2
penalty term to the objective function, which helps in reducing the
magnitude of the weights and thereby improves generalization. The objective
function for ridge regression is:

This baseline model serves as a benchmark for comparison with more complex
deep learning models, such as LSTM, presented in the next section, to evaluate
the improvement in glucose prediction accuracy provided by capturing temporal
dependencies in the data.
3.5 Long Short Term Memory Network
Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs) are well-suited to handle the challenging
task of blood glucose prediction. They excel in this context due to their inherent
capability to capture temporal dependencies in sequential data. Blood glucose
levels, being a time series, contain valuable information in their temporal pat-
terns and trends, especially in response to factors like meals, exercise, and insulin
administration. RNNs can eﬀectively model these dependencies, making them
suitable for forecasting glucose levels. However, it’s important to acknowledge
some challenges inherent to traditional RNNs, such as the vanishing gradient
problem when dealing with long sequences. This issue can hinder the network’s
ability to capture long-range dependencies in the data.
This is where Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks come into play.
LSTMs are a specialized type of RNN designed to address these problems. They
introduce a memory cell and gating mechanism that allow for the retention of
relevant information over extended periods, thereby alleviating the vanishing
gradient issue. The LSTM cell consists of several gates: the input gate (i
t
), for-
get gate (f
t
), output gate (o
t
), and a memory cell (C
t
). These gates regulate the
ﬂow of information in and out of the memory cell, allowing the LSTM to eﬀec-
tively capture the intricate dynamics of blood glucose variations and making it
more robust and accurate for this speciﬁc application.

Importantly, LSTMs can handle feature extraction automatically. The network’s
gating mechanisms, including input, forget, and output gates, regulate the ﬂow
12 C. Amodeo
of information in and out of these cells. Through these gates, LSTMs can selec-
tively focus on relevant patterns and discard less important information, eﬀec-
tively identifying salient features within the time series data. As a result, LSTMs
autonomously learn to extract and weigh the most signiﬁcant temporal features
from the raw signals, enabling them to adapt to the inherent complexity and
dynamics of glucose levels and improve prediction accuracy, with a minimum
preprocessing which will be described in the next paragraph.
As stated in section 3.2, the training objective is to minimize the Mean Squared
Error (MSE) between predicted blood glucose levels (ˆy
i
) and actual values (y
i
).
By minimizing the MSE, the model is trained to generate predictions that are
as close as possible to the actual CGM values, thus optimizing the performance
for blood glucose prediction.
The major issue in using the raw data as input for the LSTM network lies in the
length and inconsistency of sampling frequencies across diﬀerent variables. Dif-
ferent physiological and behavioral signals in the OhioT1DM dataset are sam-
pled at various frequencies, making data preprocessing crucial for consistency
and eﬀective model training. To align with the continuous glucose monitoring
(CGM) data, which is sampled every 5 minutes, all other inputs are aggregated
or resampled using a 5-minute window. This approach ensures that the temporal
resolution of all variables is consistent, making it feasible to input them into the
LSTM model.
By employing a uniform 5-minute window, the dimensionality of higher-frequency
data is reduced while preserving essential temporal information. This strategy
allows us to eﬀectively capture the high-level patterns and maintain the integrity
of critical features for our task. The resulting sequence length is now manageable
for our LSTM architecture.
The LSTM itself has been implemented using the TensorFlow framework. Each
LSTM layer consists of 32 neurons, with 2 LSTM layers in total. Training was
conducted for 500 epochs.

5 Conclusion and Future Work
This project demonstrates the feasibility of combining signal processing and ma-
chine learning techniques with CGM and physiological data to accurately predict
glucose levels over time, which is crucial for the closed-loop problem in the con-
text of artiﬁcial pancreas systems. By providing a reliable prediction horizon of
glucose levels, the proposed method can support more informed decision-making
for insulin delivery algorithms, improving the management of diabetes.
However, the proposed method has certain limitations. As observed in the quali-
tative prediction plots (Figure 8) and the Clarke Error Grid diagrams (Figure 9),
while the classical machine learning metrics (such as rMSE and MAE) indicate
good performance, there are instances where clinically signiﬁcant events are mis-
classiﬁed. For example, hypoglycemic events are sometimes predicted as normal,
and hyperglycemia may also be misclassiﬁed, which could have serious implica-
tions for patient safety.
Signal Processing Engineering for BGLP 17
Future work will focus on addressing these limitations by incorporating a better-
designed loss function that accounts for the clinical risk of misclassifying critical
glucose events. Speciﬁcally, weighting the penalty more heavily for false positives
or false negatives in hypoglycemia and hyperglycemia scenarios would help mit-
igate these risks. Additionally, data augmentation techniques, which have not
been considered in this project, could be explored to improve model robustness
and generalizability, particularly in cases where data is sparse or imbalanced.
These improvements could lead to a more reliable and clinically applicable glu-
cose prediction model that further enhances the performance of closed-loop in-
sulin delivery systems.
